<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="docker-compose-patterns">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>infra</group>
    <domain>server-craft</domain>
    <summary>Docker Compose V2 patterns for stateful infrastructure on a single VPS: port binding to 127.0.0.1, healthchecks, named volumes, resource limits, log rotation.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>docker</tag>
      <tag>docker-compose</tag>
      <tag>infrastructure</tag>
      <tag>vps</tag>
      <tag>postgres</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Docker Compose Patterns</title>
    <summary>Docker Compose V2 patterns for running stateful infrastructure services (PostgreSQL, Redis, RabbitMQ) on a single VPS alongside systemd application services. Bind database ports to 127.0.0.1 to prevent Docker from bypassing UFW. Every service referenced by depends_on: condition: service_healthy must have a healthcheck block — without it the condition is silently ignored. Use named volumes (not bind mounts) for all database data.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>For solo developer VPS platforms, containerizing infrastructure (databases, brokers, caches) while running application code as systemd services gives the best of both worlds: reproducible infrastructure setup without Docker overhead in the hot path of Python/Node services. The specific pitfall that causes production incidents: Docker inserts iptables ACCEPT rules that bypass UFW, so a port bound to 0.0.0.0:5432 is reachable from the internet regardless of firewall rules.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Running PostgreSQL, Redis, RabbitMQ, or monitoring tools on a single server.</item>
        <item>Multi-service development stack where services need to discover each other by name.</item>
        <item>Infrastructure that should survive application deploys (DB persists across deploy.sh runs).</item>
        <item>Adding optional services (monitoring, pgadmin) via compose profiles.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Running application code (Python, Node.js apps) in containers when they are deployed via rsync — adds complexity without benefit.</item>
        <item>Multi-host deployments — use Kubernetes or Docker Swarm.</item>
        <item>When the application requires direct access to /proc or host namespaces.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="port-binding-ufw-bypass">
      <rule>
        <statement>Always bind infrastructure ports to 127.0.0.1, never 0.0.0.0. Docker inserts iptables ACCEPT rules that bypass UFW — a port bound to 0.0.0.0:5432 is reachable from the internet regardless of ufw status.</statement>
        <rationale>Docker modifies iptables at a lower level than UFW. UFW rules are inserted into the ufw-user-input chain, but Docker's DNAT rules are in the DOCKER chain which is evaluated first. There is no UFW-level fix; the only reliable solution is binding to 127.0.0.1.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
ports:
  - "127.0.0.1:5432:5432"    # Only localhost can connect
  - "127.0.0.1:6379:6379"
]]></code>
      </example>
      <antipattern>
        <description>ports: - "5432:5432" (binds to all interfaces)</description>
        <reason>Equivalent to 0.0.0.0:5432:5432. Database is internet-accessible even with UFW blocking port 5432, because Docker bypasses UFW via iptables DNAT.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="healthchecks-depends-on">
      <rule>
        <statement>Every service referenced by depends_on: condition: service_healthy must have a healthcheck: block. Without it, service_healthy is silently ignored and depends_on behaves as service_started.</statement>
        <rationale>When healthcheck is missing, Docker Compose has no signal for "ready" — it falls back to "started" (the container exists), which for PostgreSQL means the process is up but not yet accepting connections. The dependent service connects, gets "connection refused", and fails to start.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
services:
  postgres:
    image: postgres:16-alpine
    healthcheck:
      test: ["CMD-SHELL", "pg_isready -U ${POSTGRES_USER} -d ${POSTGRES_DB}"]
      interval: 10s
      timeout: 5s
      retries: 5
      start_period: 30s

  api:
    depends_on:
      postgres:
        condition: service_healthy   # REQUIRES healthcheck block above
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="named-volumes">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use named volumes (pgdata:, redis-data:) for all database data directories. Never use bind mounts for database storage.</statement>
        <rationale>Named volumes are managed by Docker, survive container recreations, and live outside the project directory. Bind mounts for PostgreSQL data cause permission issues (the postgres user inside the container has a different UID than the host) and are not portable between environments.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
services:
  postgres:
    volumes:
      - pgdata:/var/lib/postgresql/data       # named volume: Docker manages it
      - ./init.sql:/docker-entrypoint-initdb.d/init.sql:ro  # bind: read-only config only

volumes:
  pgdata:    # declaration; Docker creates /var/lib/docker/volumes/<project>_pgdata/
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="resource-limits">
      <rule>
        <statement>Set deploy.resources.limits on every long-running container. Without limits, a PostgreSQL vacuum or RabbitMQ memory flood can consume all available RAM and trigger OOM kills of unrelated processes.</statement>
        <rationale>deploy.resources is supported by docker compose up in Compose V2. The limits.memory value causes the container to receive SIGKILL (not graceful shutdown) when exceeded — set it higher than the expected peak, not the steady-state usage.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
services:
  postgres:
    deploy:
      resources:
        limits:
          memory: 4G
          cpus: "2.0"
        reservations:
          memory: 512M
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="log-rotation">
      <rule>
        <statement>Set logging.options.max-size and max-file on every service, or configure it globally in /etc/docker/daemon.json. Without log rotation, container logs grow unbounded and fill the disk.</statement>
        <rationale>Docker's default json-file driver writes one log file per container with no size limit. A chatty service (RabbitMQ, nginx) can fill a 50 GB disk in hours without rotation. Three files x 10 MB = 30 MB max per service is a safe default.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
services:
  postgres:
    logging:
      driver: json-file
      options:
        max-size: "10m"
        max-file: "3"
]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="json"><![CDATA[
// /etc/docker/daemon.json (global default for all containers)
{
  "log-driver": "json-file",
  "log-opts": {
    "max-size": "10m",
    "max-file": "3"
  }
}
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="network-isolation">
      <rule>
        <statement>Create a named backend network with internal: true for database and broker services. Only add the backend network to services that need database access.</statement>
        <rationale>An internal: true network has no internet egress — containers on it cannot make outbound HTTP calls or be accessed from outside. This limits the blast radius of a compromised container: it can reach the database but not exfiltrate data to the internet.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
services:
  postgres:
    networks: [backend]
  redis:
    networks: [backend]
  api:
    networks: [backend]   # needs DB access
    ports: ["127.0.0.1:8000:8000"]

networks:
  backend:
    driver: bridge
    internal: true
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="infrastructure-stack-design">
      <p>Run stateful infrastructure (PostgreSQL, Redis, RabbitMQ) in Docker Compose. Run application code (Python/Node services) as systemd user services. This gives reproducible infrastructure setup without container overhead in the application hot path.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Do not run Python or Node.js application services in Docker Compose on a VPS where they are deployed via rsync. The rsync/systemd pattern is simpler and faster; Docker adds a layer of indirection with no benefit.</statement>
        <rationale>rsync deploys run in milliseconds and require no image builds. systemd user services restart on crash, log to journald, and have resource limits. Adding Docker to this stack for application code requires Dockerfile maintenance, image builds, and volume mounts — all overhead without a corresponding benefit on a single-server setup.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="profile-pattern">
      <rule>
        <statement>Assign optional monitoring and admin tools to named profiles (monitoring, dev). They do not start with docker compose up -d but are available on demand with --profile monitoring.</statement>
        <rationale>Flower (Celery monitor), pgAdmin, and Prometheus are useful for debugging but consume RAM constantly when running. Profiles let you activate them for a session without permanently altering the production stack.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
services:
  # Always runs
  postgres:
    image: postgres:16-alpine

  # Only with: docker compose --profile monitoring up -d
  flower:
    image: mher/flower
    profiles: ["monitoring"]
    ports: ["127.0.0.1:5555:5555"]

  pgadmin:
    image: dpage/pgadmin4
    profiles: ["dev"]
    ports: ["127.0.0.1:5050:80"]
]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
docker compose up -d                          # postgres + redis + rabbitmq only
docker compose --profile monitoring up -d     # + flower
docker compose --profile monitoring --profile dev up -d  # + flower + pgadmin
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="environment-variable-precedence">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use a single .env file next to docker-compose.yml for Compose variable substitution. For secrets passed into containers, use env_file: pointing to the same file. Shell environment variables take precedence over .env.</statement>
        <rationale>Compose reads .env automatically for ${VARIABLE} substitution in the YAML. Containers only see variables passed via environment: or env_file:. Keeping both in the same file avoids duplication and ensures the container environment matches the Compose interpolation context.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Precedence (highest to lowest):
1. Shell environment variables         (set before running docker compose)
2. .env file (Compose interpolation)   (project_dir/.env)
3. env_file: directive                 (per-service secrets file)
4. environment: directive defaults     (inline in YAML)
]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
services:
  postgres:
    image: postgres:${POSTGRES_VERSION:-16}-alpine   # interpolated from .env
    env_file: [.env]                                 # passed into container
    environment:
      POSTGRES_USER: ${POSTGRES_USER}
      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: ${POSTGRES_PASSWORD}
      POSTGRES_DB: ${POSTGRES_DB}
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="restart-policy">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use restart: unless-stopped on all infrastructure services. This restarts on crash and after host reboot, but respects an explicit docker compose down (useful for maintenance).</statement>
        <rationale>restart: always would restart a container you explicitly stopped with docker stop or docker compose down. unless-stopped is the correct production policy: restart on crash and reboot, but respect intentional stops.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="systemd-to-docker-connection">
      <p>Application services running as systemd user services connect to Docker containers via localhost and the bound port.</p>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# ~/workspace/.env (shared by both Docker Compose and systemd services)
DATABASE_URL=postgresql://nero:${POSTGRES_PASSWORD}@127.0.0.1:5432/nero_db
REDIS_URL=redis://127.0.0.1:6379/0
RABBITMQ_URL=amqp://nero:${RABBITMQ_PASSWORD}@127.0.0.1:5672/nero

# Compose binds ports to 127.0.0.1:5432, 127.0.0.1:6379, 127.0.0.1:5672
# Systemd services load .env and connect via localhost
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/infra-stack.yml" purpose="Ready-to-use postgres + redis + rabbitmq with healthchecks, named volumes, backend network"/>
      <template path="templates/monitoring.yml" purpose="Prometheus + Grafana + node-exporter as a profiles-gated monitoring stack"/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
